[
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q072",
    "type": "worked_problem",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "k-maps",
    "stem": "Find the function representation for the following K-Map:",
    "stemFigure": "/figures/ce2016-q072.png",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "F = X Z + X'Z'",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 72
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "5f11c398f4896bd2eff9d109a3102a94e12a1ba9",
    "explanation": "The 1s sit exactly where X and Z hold the same value: one group of four covers X=0,Z=0 and another covers X=1,Z=1. Inside each group the remaining variables take every combination, so they cancel out, leaving F = X'Z' + XZ (which is X XNOR Z)."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q073",
    "type": "worked_problem",
    "topic": "number-systems",
    "subtopic": "base-conversion",
    "stem": "(1001101)₂ = ( ____________ )₁₀ = ( ______________ )₁₆ = ( _______________ )₈.",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "( 77 )₁₀ = ( 4D )₁₆ = (115)₈",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 73
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "0242b9267a89aa406b393f550f6ecc6c4b1127b9",
    "explanation": "Decimal: 1001101 = 64 + 8 + 4 + 1 = 77. Hex: group in 4s from the right, 100 1101 -> 0100 1101 = 4 D. Octal: group in 3s from the right, 1 001 101 -> 1 1 5. Grouping must always start at the right-hand (least significant) end; padding on the wrong side is the classic error here."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q074",
    "type": "worked_problem",
    "topic": "number-systems",
    "subtopic": "base-conversion",
    "stem": "(36CA)₁₆ = ( ____________ )₁₀ = ( ______________ )₂ = ( _______________ )₈.",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "(14026)₁₀ = (11011011001010)₂ = (33312)₈",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 74
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "53d2a19c9d4d41948980ed3e62fbccd10e8a1fd8",
    "explanation": "Decimal: 3*4096 + 6*256 + C(12)*16 + A(10) = 12288 + 1536 + 192 + 10 = 14026. Binary: expand each hex digit to 4 bits, 3=0011, 6=0110, C=1100, A=1010 -> 0011 0110 1100 1010, i.e. 11011011001010. Octal: regroup those bits in 3s from the right, 011 011 011 001 010 -> 33312."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q075",
    "type": "short_answer",
    "topic": "computer-architecture",
    "subtopic": "addressing-modes",
    "stem": "Give an example for each of the following memory addressing modes:\nA. Register Direct: ………………………………\nB. Immediate: ……………………………………..\nC. Register Indirect: …………………………….\nD. Register Indirect- Indexed Basic: ………………………",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "A. Move R1,R2 (move R1 to R2)\nB. Move #X,R1 (move X to R1)\nC. Move (A0),R1 ([A0] → R1)\nD. Move X(A0),R1 ([[A0]+X] → R1)",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 75
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "9442edad2e8959d86dfc83154a39c82376dbc89d",
    "explanation": "Each mode differs in how many levels of lookup are needed to reach the operand. Register direct (MOVE R1,R2) uses the register's contents itself; immediate (MOVE #X,R1) carries the literal inside the instruction; register indirect (MOVE (A0),R1) treats the register as a pointer and fetches memory at [A0]; indexed register indirect (MOVE X(A0),R1) adds the displacement X to the base register first, fetching from [A0]+X."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q076",
    "type": "worked_problem",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "timing-diagrams",
    "stem": "For a positive edge-triggered T-FlipFlop, what would be the signal for Q in the following timing diagram:",
    "stemFigure": "/figures/ce2016-q076.png",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "See the model-answer figure: the Q waveform is drawn beneath the Clock and T waveforms.",
    "answerFigure": "/figures/ce2016-q076-answer.png",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 76
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "5e2fadc04db31dddf5151cac7c74c713f899cac4",
    "explanation": "A T flip-flop toggles Q on each active clock edge only when T = 1, and holds Q unchanged when T = 0. Sample T at the rising edges only: T = 1,0,1,1 with Q starting at 0 gives Q = 1, 1, 0, 1. The trap is treating T as a level (making Q follow T) or reacting to the falling edge."
  },
