  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q004",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "data-structures-algorithms",
    "subtopic": "graph-algorithms",
    "stem": "The minimum spanning tree is solved by",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Huffman",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Prim",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Dijkstra",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "DFS (Depth First Search)",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "37ea993ae2b0adb58c7ba8a27fcbd755a3fd557d",
    "explanation": "Prim's algorithm greedily grows a minimum spanning tree by repeatedly adding the cheapest edge leaving the tree (Kruskal also solves MST). The trap is Dijkstra: it has a near-identical greedy shape but minimizes path cost from a source, not total tree weight. Huffman builds an optimal prefix code and DFS is only a traversal."
  },
