  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q007",
    "type": "short_answer",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "flip-flops",
    "stem": "The truth table of a D flip flop?",
    "stemFigure": "/figures/knpc2016-q007.png",
    "options": [],
    "answerOptionLabels": [],
    "answerText": "Q=0, D=0 -> Q(t+1)=0; Q=0, D=1 -> Q(t+1)=1; Q=1, D=0 -> Q(t+1)=0; Q=1, D=1 -> Q(t+1)=1 (see figure)",
    "referenceUrl": "http://electronicspost.com/flip-flops/",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "c249997b4fab0fd21688afc254cd35c6e18badb0",
    "explanation": "A D flip-flop simply latches its input on the clock edge: Q(t+1) = D, independent of the present state Q. So D=0 gives Q(t+1)=0 and D=1 gives Q(t+1)=1 whether Q was 0 or 1, which is why it is used as a one-bit store or one-clock delay."
  },
